    <title>Combined summary - Message Signing based authentication</title>
    <updated>2023-06-07T19:01:38.657482+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2013-December/003812.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>The discussions in this context cover various topics related to cryptocurrency and authentication methods. One important thread of discussion is the use of passwords as an inefficient method of authentication due to frequent breaches and stolen databases. As an alternative, a new authentication method called Message Signing was introduced in celebration of the 5th anniversary of the Bitcoin whitepaper. This method involves the server providing a token for the client to sign, which is then validated by the server, along with the alias and bitcoin address for identification.SSL client certificates and PKI are also mentioned as potential authentication methods, although concerns were raised about the dominance of major players like Facebook and webmail providers. The storage of private keys in cryptocurrency is discussed, with suggestions to use hardware wallets like Trezor and SQRL, a simplified authentication system that uses QR codes. Another topic of discussion revolves around the security of token signing and the need to ensure that clients do not sign arbitrary strings that could be harmful. Suggestions include XORing the string with a randomly generated nonce before signing it to ensure security. There is also discussion on the issue of signing a refund transaction before the original transaction is broadcast, which raises concerns about spending users' coins unknowingly. The relevance of Bitcoin to identity systems for the web is questioned, with some members suggesting that SSL client certificates could make it more difficult for the NSA to log web traffic, but others dismissing this idea as a conspiracy theory. Additionally, there is a conversation on passwordless secure login based on bitcoin/bitmessage technology, which aims to create a secure login without requiring a password. Overall, the conversations demonstrate the complexity of designing secure and user-friendly authentication methods that can effectively address the challenges of identity and security in the digital age. It is emphasized that use cases should be grounded in actual needs rather than taking shortcuts, and unique EC keys and addresses must be used for each transaction.</summary>
